ce:section.ce:para:
The proposed Zn-doped carbon quantum dots (CQDs)-based fluorescent nano-sensor was used to detect Tar in orange juice, soft drinks, and candy samples, as presented in Table 1
                        . Due to the excellent selectivity and high sensitivity of this fluorescence sensor, complex food samples can be directly analyzed with minimal sample pretreatment. The analytical results indicate that high recovery values were obtained, ranging from 89% to 102.23%, with relative standard deviations (RSDs) between 0.98% and 1.47% (n = 3). The proposed Zn-doped CQDs-based fluorescent nano-sensor is more economical, simpler, and faster (Manikandan & Lee, 2022; Sharma et al., 2022). The results further reveal that the developed sensor based on Zn-doped CQDs has good accuracy, reproducibility, practicability, and reliability, and can be satisfactorily employed for detecting Tar in actual food samples. Compared to other methods (Table 2
                        ), our proposed approach is characterized by its simplicity, cost-effectiveness, low detection limit, and environmentally friendly synthesis process. These advantages make it a more attractive option for researchers seeking efficient and sustainable solutions in this field.
